<HL>
   Britain's GDP Rose in Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Britain's first-quarter real gross domestic
product, measured by the output of goods and services, rose a
preliminary 0.4% from the fourth quarter and 1.5% from a year
earlier, the Central Statistics Office said.
   The output-based GDP is considered the most reliable guide
to short-term movements in the economy. Britain also
calculates GDP based on expenditure and income data, and
publishes an average estimate of the three GDP measures,
which is considered the best guide to long-term movements in
the economy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Real GDP in the index, which is based on January 1985
equaling 100, was 117.3 in the first quarter, 116.8 in the
1989 fourth quarter, and 115.6 in the 1989 first quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
