<HL>
   Business Brief -- Mark IV Industries:
   Firm's Dayco Unit Reaches
   Pact to End 24-Day Strike
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR IV
</CO>
<LP>
   Mark IV Industries Inc. said its Dayco subsidiary reached
a five-year agreement with the United Rubber Workers to end a
24-day strike at its Waynesville, N.C., plant.
   Mark IV said it expects first-quarter earnings to be
reduced by about $650,000, or four cents per fully diluted
share, from the strike. But the quarter's earnings should
"compare favorably" to last year, said Sal H. Alfiero, Mark
IV chairman.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the year-ago quarter, the Amherst, N.Y.-based maker of
industrial products earned net income of $6.1 million, or 58
cents a share. On a fully diluted basis, the year-ago net was
50 cents a share. The year-ago figures include a gain of
$700,000 on the sale of securities.
   No terms of the labor pact were disclosed, but company
officials called it a "non-inflationary" pact that would make
the Waynesville facility more competitive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900530-0071
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900530-0071.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Money Rates
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP CANDA JAPAN FNM FRE MER GM
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   Tuesday, May 29, 1990
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   The key U.S. and foreign annual interest rates below are a
guide to general levels but don't always represent actual
transactions.
                                                                                                       

   PRIME RATE: 10%. The base rate on corporate loans at large
U.S. money center commercial banks.
                                                                                                       

   FEDERAL FUNDS: 8 5/16% high, 8 1/4% low, 8 3/16% near
closing bid, 8 1/4% offered. Reserves traded among commercial
banks for overnight use in amounts of $1 million or more.
Source: Fulton Prebon (U.S.A.) Inc.
                                                                                                       

   DISCOUNT RATE: 7%. The charge on loans to depository
institutions by the New York Federal Reserve Bank.
                                                                                                       

