<HL>
   EC Consumer Price Index
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<LP>
   BRUSSELS -- Pushed by sharp rises in Britain, Portugal and
Greece, the consumer price index for the 12 European
Community countries rose a preliminary 0.9% in April, faster
than the increases of 0.5% in March and 0.8% a year earlier,
Eurostat, the EC's statistics agency, said.
   The index for the EC as a whole, which is weighted to
reflect consumption of household goods in each EC country,
rose 5.4% in the 12 months through April, higher than the
4.7% increase in the U.S. and the 2.4% rise in Japan for the
same period. Eurostat said a 3% surge in Britain's index for
April -- the highest since 3.4% in April 1980 -- accounted
for a large part of the EC-wide increase. Greece's index rose
1.7% and Portugal's 1.2%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Britain's inflation figures for April normally reflect the
consequences of measures announced in the British budget,
Eurostat said, but this year, they were pushed up by the
introduction of the community charge, or so-called poll tax,
on adults; rises in excise duties on alcohol, tobacco, and
gasoline; and increases in public utilities, rents and
seasonal food costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900530-0040
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900530-0040.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Canadian Pacific Plan
   For Prime Real Estate
   Possibly Stalled by City
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CP CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- Development of 35 acres of prime downtown land
owned by the real estate unit of Canadian Pacific Ltd. could
be delayed by the city council's order to review existing
zoning plans for the area.
   Canadian Pacific's Marathon Realty Co. said it "will
pursue whatever means are available" to uphold its rights to
develop the block of land, which is only steps from Toronto's
financial district. A move by the city to reduce the amount
of commercial development currently permitted on Marathon's
site could significantly lower the property's value.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The conflict with City Hall comes when Canadian Pacific is
due to spin off 80% of Marathon to its shareholders. Canadian
Pacific is awaiting court approval of the spinoff.
   Although Marathon officials are concerned about what they
see as a breach of faith by City Hall over planning
regulations, they downplay the effects the controversy will
have on Marathon's operations as a public concern.
   "A delay in one project doesn't fundamentally affect the
viability of the company," said John Beales, Marathon's
senior vice president, buildings.
   Marathon plans to build up to six million square feet of
office space on the site over the next 10 to 15 years. A 3/4
acre piece of land adjacent to the Marathon holding is
reported to have sold recently for more than 240 million
Canadian dollars (US$203 million). Brad Smith, analyst with
Toronto-based Nesbitt Thomson Deacon Inc., said the 35-acre
block owned by Marathon represents about 20% of the company's
net asset value. The property is part of a 200-acre section
of a rail corridor that surrounds the central train station.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900530-0039
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900530-0039.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Washington Bancorp.
   To Issue $45 Million
   In New Secured Debt
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   WWBC
</CO>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Washington Bancorp. said it plans to issue
$45 million in new secured debt to private investors to ease
the bank holding company's current liquidity crunch.
   The new debt will be secured by virtually all the assets
of the company, and the investors will receive warrants to
acquire a "major" stock interest, the amount of which is
still being negotiated. John M. Toups, chairman and chief
executive officer, said he was not pleased about the likely
dilution of the common stock, but added, "You've got to offer
something."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Earlier this month, Washington Bancorp. said it wouldn't
be able to repay about $36.7 million of unsecured commercial
paper obligations because certain credit lines were cut off.
   While purchasers for all of the new bonds have not yet
been found, those committed to buying a portion of the notes
include Wafic Said, whose family trust and related entities
own about 27% of the company, and John J. Mason, who owns a
6.4% stake.
   After the immediate liquidity needs of the company are
met, Washington Bancorp. plans to raise additional funds by
issuing more equity, probably through a rights offering, Mr.
Toups said.
   Mr. Toups added that the company is scaling back its
operations to reduce its capital needs, particularly by
getting out of the mortgage banking and venture-capital
businesses. "We're going to stay close to home," Mr. Toups
said.
</TEXT>
