<HL>
   Technology:
   Genentech Asks FDA
   To Back Drug Test
   For Cystic Fibrosis
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   GNE
</CO>
<IN>
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)
</IN>
<GV>
FOOD AND DRUG ADMINISTRATION (FDA)
</GV>
<LP>
   SOUTH SAN FRANCISCO -- Genentech Inc. said it asked the
U.S. Food and Drug Administration to approve a human clinical
test of a potential new drug against cystic fibrosis.
   Cystic fibrosis, a hereditary disease that affects one in
every 2,500 babies born in the U.S., is marked by thick lung
secretions that often lead to respiratory failure and death
by age 28. Currently, there are an estimated 30,000 young
people with the disease in this country.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The experimental treatment is based upon a concept that
has been around since the 1950s. Decades ago, scientists
found that a certain cow enzyme could dissolve excess amounts
of DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid) in the lung secretions, making
them more liquid and easier to clear from the breathing
passages. But the cow enzyme provoked allergic reactions, and
never became standard treatment.
   The biotech firm said its scientists used gene-splicing
technology to insert the gene for the human form of this
enzyme into mammalian cells. The cells produce a purified
form of the human enzyme, called DNase. Genentech said few
allergic reactions are expected because the engineered enzyme
mimics the natural form already found in the human body.
   Genentech said it hopes to test DNase in an aerosolized
form in young adults with cystic fibrosis. After determining
its safety and appropriate dose levels, the company plans to
launch studies in younger children.
   If shown to be useful against cystic fibrosis, the drug
may be tested against other lung ailments, such as bacterial
pneumonia, chronic bronchitis and emphysema, Genentech added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900530-0018
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900530-0018.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Canada Extends Line
   Of Credit to Assist
   Exports to U.S.S.R.
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   OTTAWA -- The Canadian government decided to extend a 500
million Canadian dollar (US$423.7 million) credit line to the
Soviet Bank for Foreign Economic Affairs (Vnesheconombank) to
assist the export of Canadian goods and services to the
Soviet Union.
   The decision was announced yesterday, the first day of a
two-day Canadian visit by Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev.
The Soviet leader is to fly to Washington later today for a
five-day U.S. visit.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The two-year credit line will be "a major asset to develop
trade with the Soviet Union," said Canadian Trade Minister
John Crosbie. It will be provided by a Canadian government
export financing agency, the Export Development Corp.
   The corporation will provide financing for as much as 85%
of the value of Canadian goods and services sold to Soviet
customers. Repayment will be made over periods ranging from
three to 8 1/2 years at fixed or floating interest rates.
   A Canadian trade official said the credit line will
replace a less-flexible supplier credit protocol with the
Soviet Union.
   Deputy Prime Minister Don Mazankowski also disclosed that
Canada and the Soviet Union have held preliminary talks on
the renewal of a grain sales agreement. The existing
five-year agreement, which expires July 31, 1991, calls for
the Soviet Union to buy at least 25 million metric tons of
Canadian wheat and feed grains during the period of the
agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
