<HL>
   CD Yields at Banks
   And Brokerage Firms
   Remain Unchanged
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Yields on certificates of deposit at major
banks and brokerage firms remained largely unchanged in the
week ended yesterday.
   Changes in average yields were mixed for
small-denomination CDs, while they remained at or above 8%
for maturities of six months and longer. The average yield on
a one-year consumer CD eased to 8% from 8.02%, while yields
on two-year consumer CDs were up to 8.12% from 8.10%,
according to figures compiled by Banxquote Money Markets, a
New York information service.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   None of the banks in Banxquote's 18-bank survey offered a
yield as high as 9%. The highest yield for a
small-denomination consumer CD was 8.76% for a five-year CD
offered by Chase Manhattan Bank in New York.
   Small-denomination CDs sold by leading broker-dealers were
also little-changed, with average yields remaining above 8%
for all maturities. Average yields on six-month CDs eased to
8.30% from 8.32%, while average yields on five-year CDs
remained at 8.63%.
   Meanwhile, average yields for large-denomination CDs,
which typically require deposits of $90,000 or more, were
down slightly for all maturities. Average yields on six-month
jumbo CDs slid to 7.89% from 7.91%, while one-year maturities
fell to 8.06% from 8.11%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900530-0015
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900530-0015.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Tyco Labs to Buy
   Operating Assets
   Of Australia Firm
   ----
   By John R. Wilke
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   TYC A.WOI
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   In a big push into Europe and the Pacific Rim, Tyco
Laboratories Inc. said it will buy the operating assets of an
Australian maker of fire-protection equipment for about $600
million in cash and stock.
   Tyco, which has a commanding share of the fast-growing
fire-protection market, said it will pay $350 million in cash
and five million shares of common stock for Wormald
International Ltd. The stock, valued at $242 million at
current prices, will represent 10.6% of shares outstanding
after closing the deal, a Tyco statement said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Separately, Irving Gutin, senior vice president, said Tyco
will report revenue of $2.1 billion for the fiscal year
ending Thursday, up from $1.97 billion in 1989. Mr. Gutin
also forecast revenue of $3.45 billion for the next fiscal
year, reflecting the Wormald acquisition.
   Investors reacted positively. In active New York Stock
Exchange composite trading, Tyco closed at $50.75 a share, up
$2.50.
   "This clearly gives Tyco the No. 1 position in the world
as a fire-control provider," said Laurence C. Baker, an
analyst with Dillon, Read &amp; Co. Based on Tyco's history with
acquisitions, the deal probably will be non-dilutive of its
stock, he said. But he added: "The question is what happens
in the short term, and we don't have enough information yet
to tell."
   The Wormald acquisition gives Tyco a strong presence in
Europe and the United Kingdom, where fiscal 1991 sales should
rise to $600 million from approximately $35 million before
the acquisition, Tyco said. In Pacific Rim nations, Tyco
projects a sales increase to $340 million from $15 million
before the acquisition. Wormald's fiscal-1991 sales in the
U.S. and Canada are projected to rise to about $210 million.
   Fire protection-making and installing sprinklers, alarms
and industrial fire-suppression systems -- is Tyco's largest
business, accounting for $1.7 billion of the projected 1991
sales of $3.45 billion. Industrial flow-control system sales
are forecast at $900 million, with electronics and packaging
accounting for the rest.
   L. Dennis Kozlowski, president and chief operating officer
and president of Tyco's Grinnell Corp. fire-protection unit,
said the fire-detection market "has grown dramatically in the
U.S. and Canada" as laws require such systems in public
buildings. He projected increased profitability as a result
of the acquisition.
   Under terms of the Wormald agreement, Tyco also will issue
a five-year warrant to buy five million additional Tyco
shares, at $70 each. Tyco said the firms agreed to appoint
representatives to their respective boards and will enter an
agreement whereby Wormald may not acquire additional shares
except under specified circumstances. Tyco also said
completion of the transaction is subject to government
approvals and a vote by Wormald shareholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900530-0014
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900530-0014.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Timken Buys Maker
   Of Precision Bearings
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TKR
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   CANTON, Ohio -- Timken Co. purchased MPB Corp. for $185
million, moving the big maker of tapered roller bearings and
specialty steels into the precision aircraft bearings market.
   MPB, which has annual sales of more than $120 million and
employs 1,850 people at plants in Keene and Lebanon, N.H., is
a major supplier of ball and roller bearings for aircraft
engines and aircraft and missile control systems. Its
bearings also are used in computer disk drives, X-ray
equipment and other precision instruments, but aircraft is
the major market, Timken said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Timken's bearings are used in automobiles, trucks,
industrial machinery and other equipment, but the company
hasn't previously participated in the precision bearings
business, said Joseph F. Toot Jr., president. He said Timken
is aware that a defense spending cutback may cut into MPB's
business, but he said strong commercial aircraft sales and
increased applications in other precision equipment will
offset any loss of defense business.
   Timken bought MPB for cash, and the price included the
cost of retiring the concern's debt, Mr. Toot said. He said
the acquisition won't dilute Timken's earnings.
   There are no plans to move any of the MPB operations nor
to change the company's management, said Peter J. Ashton,
Timken executive vice president, bearings. Thomas Uhlig is
president and chief executive officer of MPB, Mr. Ashton
said.
</TEXT>
