900530-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Federal Express Gets Clearance to Merge
   Its Pilot Seniority List With That of Tiger
   ----
   By Peter Waldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   FDX LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
AIR FREIGHT (AIF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Federal Express Corp., overcoming a hurdle that has caused
inefficiencies for the struggling company, said a government
arbitrator cleared the way for the merger of its pilot
seniority list with the seniority list of pilots acquired
with Tiger International Corp.
   But the good news for the company isn't being greeted that
way by some of the affected pilots.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Memphis, Tenn., air express giant has been operating
with two separate pilot lists since buying Tiger last year,
pending arbitration. The company's inability to merge its
roughly 2,000-person pilot force -- comprised of roughly half
former Tiger aviators -- has hampered Federal Express's
efforts to meld the Tiger fleet into its own air operations,
costing the company as much as $150 million a year in
possible savings, analysts have estimated.
   "The decision will now permit the company to integrate the
two pilot groups and achieve greater efficiencies in its air
operations," said Frederick W. Smith, Federal Express's
chairman and chief executive officer.
   But arbitrator George Nicoloau's ruling hasn't ended the
bitter strife within the company over the pilot
seniority-list question. Many longtime Federal Express pilots
fell hundreds of places on the new, merged list, fanning
already bitter feelings over a promise they say Federal made
to them several years ago to "end-tail" -- or put at the
bottom of the list -- aviators acquired in future mergers or
acquisitions. The issue has become a staple gripe at informal
meetings being held on the possible organization of an
independent pilots' union at the company.
   "I feel like we got cheated again," said Richard Sowers, a
Boeing 727 first officer who fell from 642 on the old list to
1,143 on the merged list. "The Fed Ex pilots are the nicest
guys in the world to fly with, but they're so naive it's
embarrassing."
   Mr. Sowers has filed suit against Federal, claiming the
company violated its employment contract with pilots by not
end-tailing the Tiger aviators and by agreeing to let the
arbitrator merge the new pilots into Federal's list. A U.S.
district court judge in Reno, Nev., is expected to rule next
month on a Federal Express motion to dismiss the case.
   But yesterday, as the arbitrator's seniority list arrived
at pilots' homes by mail, Mr. Sowers's lawyer, Leo Donahue of
Sacramento, Calif., said he received calls from some 15
disappointed Federal pilots inquiring how they can join the
suit. Yesterday's calls were on top of dozens of prior
inquiries from pilots in recent weeks, he said.
   "If we get through the motion {for dismissal}, we estimate
we'll have the majority of the crew force in the suit," said
Mr. Donahue.
   A Federal spokeswoman declined to comment on the
litigation, but Mr. Smith has said the contract with the
company's pilots wasn't meant to limit Federal's flexibility
in a merger.
   Gregory Chappars, a 727 captain who went from 284 on the
old list to 515 on the merged list, praised the fairness of
the arbitrator's list, but said some Federal pilots are angry
with the company's recent attempts to change work rules. In
the wake of five consecutive quarters of falling year-to-year
profits, the company has moved to revoke some of the very
vacation perks that management praised so heartily during a
union-affiliation drive last fall, Mr. Chappars said.
Pro-union pilots were trounced in that election.
   "As soon as the union vote was over," said Mr. Chappars,
who said he voted against the union, "they started seeking to
modify those various policies to make working conditions more
onerous." Federal Express officials couldn't be reached for
comment late yesterday evening.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900530-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900530-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Software Sales in U.S.
   Grew at Healthy Rate
   In the First Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<IN>
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Software Publishers Association said
domestic software sales grew at a surprisingly healthy rate
in the first quarter.
   North American sales grew 26%, and international sales by
U.S. software companies jumped even higher -- by 50% -- in
the same period. The news is a major departure from 1989,
when the annual growth rate in domestic software sales slowed
to 12% from the previous year; in 1988, by contrast, the
annual growth rate was up 40% from 1987.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The bright figures "shocked us," said the association's
research director, Ann Stephens, who said that the first
quarter is generally the software industry's slowest season.
   Ms. Stephens attributed the growth largely to the
introduction of a plethora of new products and upgrades and
to improved distribution controls. Most encouraging, she
said, is evidence that the sales surge is highest in
traditional categories like spreadsheets and word processors,
"which shows that fundamentally the industry is doing well."
   Word processors had the largest and fastest growth for the
period, with $117 million in sales, an 88% rise. The SPA data
are based on monthly sales information from 150 leading PC
software publishers.
   "The popular wisdom was that domestic sales have stalled,"
said SPA executive director Ken Wasch. "But this is the best
quarter we've had in years." And preliminary numbers for
April, he said, suggest that the sales improvement will
continue.
   Mr. Wasch partly credited a crackdown on illegal software
copying -- an anti-piracy campaign that was spearheaded by
his association last year and reinforced by several recent
and hefty court settlements on the issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
